A Jenkins agent is a worker node that executes build and deployment jobs assigned by the Jenkins controller. 
Agents help distribute workloads, run builds in parallel, and support different environments such as Linux, Windows, Docker, 
and Kubernetes. I have configured SSH-based agents by creating nodes, assigning labels, configuring SSH credentials, and 
troubleshooting issues related to connectivity, disk-space monitoring, Java installation, and agent availability.

# Pipeline
A Jenkins Pipeline is a way to define the entire CI/CD process as code using a Jenkinsfile.

Instead of configuring jobs manually through the UI, all stages such as build, test, scan, and deploy are written in code and 
stored in Git.

Developer Pushes Code
          |
          v
      Jenkins
          |
   ----------------
   |      |       |
 Build   Test   Deploy
          |
       Production

#Types
1. Declarative Pipeline (Most Common)
Easy to read and maintain.

pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {
        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn clean package'
            }
        }

        stage('Test') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn test'
            }
        }
    }
}

2. Scripted Pipeline
Uses Groovy scripting.


node {
    stage('Build') {
        sh 'mvn clean package'
    }

    stage('Test') {
        sh 'mvn test'
    }
}






# Real-Time DevOps Pipeline Example


pipeline {
    agent any

    stages {

        stage('Checkout') {
            steps {
                git 'https://github.com/company/app.git'
            }
        }

        stage('Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn clean package'
            }
        }

        stage('SonarQube Scan') {
            steps {
                sh 'mvn sonar:sonar'
            }
        }

        stage('Docker Build') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker build -t app:v1 .'
            }
        }

        stage('Push Image') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker push app:v1'
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                sh 'kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml'
            }
        }
    }
}